Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Write your code here
print("Null Items Count:", food_hub_data.isnull().sum().sum())
print("Na Items Count:", food_hub_data.isna().sum().sum())
print("Missing Ratings Count:", len(food_hub_data.loc[food_hub_data["rating"] == "Not given"]))

#Since impudation for the rating is risky, and we know that in general not leaving a rating is a valid input, it is best
#to create a subset of the data where the "Not given" values are dropped. The subset of data can be used for any sort
#of evaluation where rating needs to be considered. Keep in mind that since there are 736 rows where the rating is not
#provided we are essentially dropping ~40% of the data.
food_hub_data_rated_only = food_hub_data.loc[food_hub_data["rating"] != "Not given"]
food_hub_data_rated_only.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
food_hub_data_rated_only["rating"] = food_hub_data_rated_only["rating"].astype(int)

print("Missing Ratings Count After Not Given Droped:", len(food_hub_data_rated_only.loc[food_hub_data_rated_only["rating"] == "Not given"]))

food_hub_data_rated_only.head()

#When evaluating
#All columns except rating are input. Predictions are based on the outputs. So rating in this case is the output, which is the most important
#Variable to look at with multi-variate analysis. multi-Variate analysis should be based on comparing all the inputs against
#the output.


#Whenever we are doing the analysis specifically related to rating we have to drop the "Not give" values.
#Whenever you are looking at all data not related to the ratings, then we can use the full data set.

#Bivariate analysis should be based on comparing inputs to output.

#We determine the output based on what it is that we are trying to predict.

  • While all the rows have values for their corresponding columns, there are still instances with the rating column where no rating is given. So we may need to consider treating these specific rows as stated previously.

  • As a callout, I split the data into 2 categories:

    • The first category is a subset of the data where all of the rows where the rating = "Not given" has been removed from the data set. This will be useful so that we can perform numeric operations on this dataset without throwing type exception errors. Furthermore, since customer ratings can't safely be impudated, we can use the subset for any data analysis that involves rating without skweing the data for ratings by utilzing the means of ratings grouped by restaurant name or cuisine type. I also type cast the rating values as an int.
    • The second category contains the full original unfilterd data set. Since all of the columns provided in the data set don't contain any missing values we can use the full data set when performing any sort of analysis that doesn't involve rating.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[37]:
twentyFivePercentRevenue = food_hub_data.loc[food_hub_data["cost_of_the_order"]>20, "cost_of_the_order"].sum() * .25

# For the fifteen percent revenue condition we need to make sure that we include only the range of costs of 6 - 20 dollars.
# Otherwise, we'd be double counting revenue for costs of orders above 20 dollars which would be incorrect.
fifteenPerecentRevenueCondition = (food_hub_data["cost_of_the_order"] > 5) & (food_hub_data["cost_of_the_order"] <= 20)
fifteenPercentRevenue = food_hub_data.loc[fifteenPerecentRevenueCondition, "cost_of_the_order"].sum() * .15
totalRevenue = twentyFivePercentRevenue + fifteenPercentRevenue

print("The 25% revenue is", twentyFivePercentRevenue)
print("The 15% revenue is", fifteenPercentRevenue)
print("The total revenue is", totalRevenue)

The 25% revenue is 3688.7275
The 15% revenue is 2477.5755000000004
The total revenue is 6166.303

Observations:

  • All the resturants that have a cost greater than 20 dollars at 25% charge generate a revenue of 3688.7275 dollars.
  • All the resturants that have a cost greater than 5 dollars at 15% charge generate a revenue of 2477.5755000000004 dollars.
  • The total revenue earned is 6166.303
  • My assumption is that the delivery company either does not charge or service orders that cost less than 5 dollars since any revenue amount for less than 5 dollars is not stated. Therefore, I won't include this in the revenue calculation. This assumption would make sense since most delivery companies have a minimal clip level that you must order in order to make it worth while for them to charge a delivery fee. Otherwise, they'd lose money on like a 4 dollar order.

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

  • Regardless of cuisine type or restaurant, the biggest determing factor for when there is peak demand is dictated by the day of the week. There are signifantly more orders placed across all the restaurants on the weekends when compared to the weekday. It would be helpful if additional information could be provided on the specific days of the week and time captured as a time stamp. This would give us the opportunity to see more specific trends on demand on specific days.

  • Approximately 33% of the revenue is driven by these these top 5 resturants:

    • Shake Shack 219
    • The Meatball Shop 132
    • Blue Ribbon Sushi 119
    • Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken 96
    • Parm 68

  • Shake Shack looks to be the most popular restaurant

  • The majority of your revenue ~is 3.85% is driven by items that > $20. This tends to suggest that most of your revenue is at the 25% of cost mark.

  • The most popular cuisine types which have the higest demand for the weekend are:

    • American 415
    • Japanese 335
    • Italian 207
    • Chinese 163

  • The higest demand is for American cuisine

  • Cuisine type seems to be the secondary driving factory for demand.

  • It would be better if we could have a different data set capture where there are a higher number of users to provide ratings. We had to skip 736 rating values since they were not provided which was about 40% of the data for any data analysis related to ratings.

  • There are roughly 600 repeat customers that continously use food hub to place their orders throughout the week.

  • The revenue gained is most likely going to be driven by the most popular restuarants and cuisine types.

Recommendations:

  • Since demand is highest on the weekends it may be worth incorporating a demand based pricing strategy similar to Uber where you can incorporate surchages to increase profitibility. Cost of the order did not significantly affect the rating, so there may be some wiggle room to to maximize profits. The benefit of introducting surge based pricing is that it can help drive increased availabiltiy of delviery personeel to make sure the level of service doesn't drop significantly bcause of busier days of the week.

  • While, the majority of your revenue ~is 3.85% is driven by items that > $20, the larger number of orders that cost less than $20 is over 96%. One optimization that could be made is either increasing the percentage that are charged at the current pricing tiers, or adding additional pricing tiers so that the business can generate more revenus in the $6-$19 priced items that make up the majority of the orders.

  • Since there are over 600 repeat customers, it may be worthwhile looking into offering repeat customers incentives in order to provide them more value so that they can do additional orders. Increased orders can lead to increased demand beyond what is seen in the current data set due to them placing larger orders. Incentivized customers that have a great experience can also lead to more better reviews for those restaurants which can in turn help drive more clients to the restuarants.

  • There may also be value in offering incentives to your highest performing restuarants to further increase demand which can lead to increased revenue. So for example, having your most popular restaurants featured as an advertisement with the Food hub app, can help bring further clients to those restaurants which leads to increased orders. This can also lead to increased reviews which is positive for those popular restaurants.

  • To further reuduce loses, it may be worth enforcing a minimum clip-level, in the event that one is not already in place, to guarantee that your minimum sale is always generating at least 15% revenue. The reason being is that currently there is no revenue made for any order amount placed under 5 dollars.

  • In order to get larger population of users to leave reviews, since we had close to 40% that did not leave a review, it may be worth offering meaningful incentives to encourage users to leave a review.

  • Something that can also enhance the overall data captured to get a better picture on what certain restaurants are rated higher than others, is to add pre-defined categories to the review that users leave so that they can quickly select categories such as cuisine type, delivery type, cost, etc that indicate why them made their rating. These types of additional items can help give more insights on demand that can lead to future business optimizations.

  • In order to get more granular to see demand by Weekend or Weekday, it would be worthwhile to capture the full time stamp of each order. This would allow the business to get further insights such as what specifc day on the weekend is most busy to do further demand and rating analysis and optimization for the business.
